insight_description: Depressive symptoms decreased as reported in surveys, aligning with increased physical activity and time outdoors.
Patient’s negative self-evaluative thoughts and perfectionism are persistent despite some improvement in mood scores.
Periods of increased physical activity and outdoor time coincide with improved positive affect and reduced negative affect.
Sleep patterns are irregular, with frequent changes in bedtime and wake time, and fragmented sleep episodes.
Patient reports physical symptoms of distress, which coincide with periods of high stress and poor sleep quality.
Social interaction is variable, with periods of increased calls and device contacts, but also frequent missed calls.
Digital engagement at home decreased over time, with shorter and fewer phone unlocks, possibly reflecting reduced motivation.
Patient identifies academic and family pressures, and poor sleep, as key triggers for emotional distress.
Despite some improvement, patient struggles to maintain coping strategies due to feeling overwhelmed and fatigued.
Patient finds grounding and mindfulness exercises helpful, but sustaining their use remains a challenge.
Periods of increased sedentary behavior alternate with bursts of activity, reflecting fluctuating energy and motivation.
Routine regularity, as measured by circadian rhythm, fluctuates and aligns with changes in sleep and activity.
Patient’s digital engagement shows cyclic patterns, with alternating periods of high and low phone use.
Patient’s social contact via Bluetooth and WiFi devices fluctuates, possibly reflecting changes in social environment.
Despite improvements in mood and activity, patient continues to experience cycles of negative thoughts and emotional distress.
